    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — from surface observation to authorial intent in canonical context. Isaiah 26 sits inside the 'Isaiah Apocalypse' (chs. 24-27) and must be read as part of that sustained vision of global judgment and cosmic renewal. The four movements below trace the chapter's argument from the eschatological city-song through the lament and into the resurrection oracle and final summons. Where Hebrew vocabulary sharpens the meaning of an English phrase, a brief Greek/Hebrew note follows as supplement.",
