        "title": "Salvation as wall — the city whose security is God Himself",
        "range": "26:1-6",
        "excerpt": "We have a strong city; He sets up walls and ramparts for security.",
        "body": "The song of verses 1-6 is not merely the opening of a poem — it is the eschatological answer to the 'city of chaos' mourned in 24:10. Where the city of human pride has been made desolate, the city of God stands strong, and the reason is given without ambiguity: its walls are *yeshuah* — salvation, God's own saving act, personified as the city's fortification. Isaiah is doing something theologically precise here. Ancient cities boasted of their walls as evidence of human engineering and military capacity. Zion's walls are God's own salvation. The city's security cannot be sieged because it is the character and action of Yahweh Himself.\n\nThe gates are opened to 'the righteous nation that remains faithful' (v. 2). Two terms define the entrant: *tsaddiq* (righteous, conforming to God's standard) and *emun* (faithful, trustworthy, those who keep faith). This is not entry by ethnic privilege but by covenantal character — a theme that reaches through Isaiah to chapters 56 and 60, where even foreigners who keep the Sabbath and hold fast the covenant are welcomed. The city's openness is broad; the criterion is moral and relational, not national.\n\nVerses 3-4 are the theological heart of the unit. The doubled *shalom* of verse 3 — 'perfect peace' — rests on a specific condition: the mind *samakh* on Yahweh. The Hebrew *samakh* is leaning-on, supporting-oneself-by — the posture of weight-bearing trust, not casual acknowledgment. The imperatives of verse 4 ('Trust in the LORD forever') ground this posture in the nature of God: He IS the everlasting Rock (*tsur olamim*). The permanence of the Rock is the theological ground of the imperative to trust without temporal limit.\n\nVerses 5-6 anchor the song in a concrete prior act of divine reversal. The 'unassailable city' (*qiryah*, the fortified town) has been humbled, laid low, cast to the dust. And the agents of its trampling are not armies but 'the foot of the afflicted, the steps of the helpless.' Isaiah consistently uses this inversion — the proud brought low by the very people they oppressed — as the signature of Yahweh's justice. The pattern anticipates the Magnificat (Luke 1:52-53) and the Beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-5).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yeshuah* (salvation, v. 1) is the same root as the name Joshua/Jesus — 'Yahweh saves.' Setting *yeshuah* as the walls of the city is proto-messianic: the salvation that God provides in Christ is itself the believer's security. *Tsur olamim* (everlasting Rock, v. 4) — *tsur* is Isaiah's characteristic rock-metaphor for Yahweh (cf. 17:10; 30:29); *olamim* is the plural of *olam* (eternity), heightening the permanence."
