        "excerpt": "Your dead will live; their corpses will rise. You who lie in the dust, awake and shout for joy.",
        "body": "Verse 19 is the chapter's theological summit and one of the Old Testament's most debated texts. The question for interpretation is whether the verse refers primarily to national restoration (Israel revived from the 'death' of exile, as in Ezekiel 37) or to literal bodily resurrection of the dead. The answer, as John Oswalt (Commentary on Isaiah, NICOT) and others have argued, is almost certainly both — a near-horizon referent (national restoration) that simultaneously points beyond itself to the eschatological resurrection. The vocabulary demands this: *nevelah* (corpses, physical bodies) and *qamay* (rise, the verb used for bodily standing up) are the most physically concrete language available. The command 'awake and shout for joy, you who lie in the dust' addresses currently dead people as recipients of future life — this is not metaphorical exile but literal entombment being reversed.\n\nThe contrast with verse 14 is decisive. There the wicked dead 'will not live, the departed spirits will not rise' — the same lemmas *chayah* and *qamay* used to deny resurrection to the enemies. Here the same language affirms it for 'Your dead' — those who belong to Yahweh. The resurrection is selective, not universal in this text: Yahweh's people rise; the oppressor-lords do not. Daniel 12:2 will later expand this to a dual resurrection (some to everlasting life, some to everlasting contempt), and Revelation 20 will specify two resurrections. Isaiah 26:19 is the prophetic seed of all of it.\n\nThe dew metaphor is among the chapter's most beautiful images. 'Your dew is as the dew of the dawn' — the morning dew appears without human agency, drawn from the sky, refreshing the parched ground before anyone has acted. So Yahweh's life-giving power descends on those who lie in the dust. The earth itself 'will give birth to the departed spirits (*rephaim*)' — the very ground that received the dead will be made to release them. Where human birth-striving produced only wind (v. 18), divine dew produces life.\n\nVerses 20-21 close the chapter with an intimate command and its cosmic ground. 'Come, my people, enter your rooms, close your doors, hide for a little while until indignation runs its course.' The Passover echo is unmistakable — the command replicates the sheltering inside while judgment passes (Exodus 12:22-23). For the believer who reads this eschatologically, the 'rooms' are the security of being in Christ while the final indignation falls. The 'little while' (*meat rega*, a small moment) is the limited duration of present suffering set against the eternal weight of glory that follows (cf. 2 Corinthians 4:17). The ground for sheltering is not the believer's own righteousness but the fact that Yahweh Himself is about to emerge from His place — the divine warrior coming out to execute justice on the earth's long-concealed iniquity. When the LORD emerges, His people are inside; when the judgment is complete, they will emerge into the world the LORD has cleansed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nevelah* (corpses, v. 19) — physical carcasses, the word used for unburied dead (e.g., Psalm 79:2); its use here insists on physicality, not mere spiritual renewal. *Tal* (dew, v. 19) — morning dew as image of God's reviving power (cf. Hosea 14:5, 'I will be like the dew to Israel'); *orah* (morning light) pairs with *tal* to create an image of new creation dawn. *Zaam* (indignation, v. 20) — divine wrath with a fixed object and duration; the same word used in Daniel 8:19; 11:36 for the eschatological period of wrath."
